I sat across from Hana at a coffee shop when she asked if options trading could “get her there faster.” She’d maxed out her brokerage app, convinced by a friend—Marisol—who’d tripled a small account in six months on a run of short-term plays. “She said it’s just about discipline,” Hana told me, “cutting losses fast, letting winners ride. She does it after work. At her kitchen table.”

Hana’s savings were earmarked for a down payment. She was close—within twelve months, she thought. But Marisol had sold her on turning that pile into something bigger. “She showed me her screen. Green line. Little profit counter ticking. It looked real.”

I asked what she’d trade with. She named a figure—fifty thousand. I paused. “So, rent’s covered, emergency fund’s separate?” She looked down. “Not exactly. I was going to wait on the emergency set-aside. Just until I got a few wins.”

Then Chidi walked in, late. Her brother. He’d helped her pick the condo. He’d built the spreadsheet. “Wait,” he said, sliding into the booth. “You’re risking the down payment?” He didn’t yell. Just leaned forward, glanced at Hana, then me. “I thought we agreed that was sacred.”

Hana said, “Marisol says it’s only risky if you get emotional.”  

Chidi didn’t answer that. He asked, “What happens if the market drops next month? Or you lose hours at work?”  

She didn’t answer.  

I asked if she’d tested her strategy with play money. She said Marisol thought that was “for people who aren’t serious.”  

Chidi looked tired. “Marisol lost three grand last year. I know because she asked me to cover her car payment. Then her rent. She didn’t tell you that part, did she?”  

Hana stared at her hands.  

He said, “I’m not saying she meant bad. But she gambled. And won once. Now she thinks it’s a plan.”  

She didn’t speak. The barista called an order. Chidi stood. “Come on. Let’s go look at the unit again. You’ve forgotten how the light hits the kitchen in the morning.”

