Dmitri wasn’t reckless—he drove the same dented hatchback for eight years and still used a coffee mug from a conference in 2017. He’d been trading small amounts of options on and off for years, mostly as a mental game, the kind of thing that made his train commute feel less passive. When Ingrid mentioned she had fifteen thousand saved for a down payment, stashed in a low-yield account, Dmitri tilted his head. “You’re just… leaving it there?” he asked. “That’s dead money, honestly. I made nearly that much last year on one biotech play. Not every month, obviously. But over time? It’s like giving your savings a job.”

Ingrid hesitated. “But I need that money. In, like, two years.”

“Right, but think of it as a side hustle for the cash,” Dmitri said. “Just a couple trades. If it works, you buy the condo sooner. If not…” He paused. “Well, I’ve had months where I lost a few hundred. Not fun, but not crippling. You’d still be ahead of most people.”

She tried it. For six weeks, she doubled her allocation on a small bet that paid off—the rush was real. Then a cryptocurrency-linked ETF she’d hedged against spiked overnight. She was wiped out in three hours on a Friday. The margin call came on Sunday morning.

Chidi, who’d been helping Ingrid review mortgage preapprovals, called Dmitri Monday evening. The line was quiet a long time after he told him. Finally, Dmitri said, “I wouldn’t have said anything if I thought she’d go all in.” He’d been planning to show her his own ledger that weekend—modest wins, consistent losses, the trade history of someone still waiting for the big one.

Ingrid hasn’t listened to his voicemail yet.

