Ingrid kept the spreadsheet open for three weekends straight, tracking strike prices and expiration dates, the same way she’d once mapped out apartment viewings. Marisol had shown her how to roll puts on a mid-cap tech stock, how a clean monthly premium could outpace savings interest ninefold. "I did it myself two years straight," Marisol said, "used it to double down on my contribution upside." It sounded like leverage, not gambling. The numbers lined up: 1.4% monthly return, annualized beyond 15%, compounded while keeping 30% in cash for margin calls.

They met in Marisol’s kitchen, coffee just off boil. She was self-taught, freelance UX, early forties, the kind of person who’d replaced her student loan with crypto gains and never looked back. Her confidence wasn’t loud; it was in the way she didn’t flinch at volatility. Ingrid had $78,000 in a high-yield savings account, earmarked for a down payment. Six months from offer submission, but Marisol said, “You’re not spending it yet. Let it work.” The first month, Ingrid cleared $1,100. She reinvested.

Then the biotech holding in her small LEAPs portfolio tanked overnight after trial results. The hedge failed. She covered, but too late to avoid a $22,000 loss. Sold ETFs to refill the emergency buffer. Missed the window on a two-bedroom near the train. 

Marisol found out at a dinner Ingrid hosted, the one where she laughed and said “Market’s a rough teacher.” Marisol didn’t touch her wine after that. Drove Ingrid to her next realtor meeting. Said nothing about adjustments to delta or implied volatility. 

The book never mentions how few margins survive a sixty-day drawdown when the money has a hard deadline. Doesn’t talk about what silence costs when you’re the one who gave the nod.  

Ingrid’s apartment search is back on. She’s added a column to her spreadsheet: “Time Horizon.”

