------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Noor still sometimes texts Dmitri when the market dips below 4 a.m. He doesn’t answer, not for hours, maybe not until lunch. But she sends the messages anyway — screenshots, candlestick patterns, red arrows pointing at things only margin traders seem to notice. She started doing this two months after she blew past her maintenance requirement on that biotech run-up. The stock had doubled overnight on trial news, and she’d doubled down with borrowed cash the next morning — clean leverage on a clean thesis, she said Dmitri called it.

Dmitri had told her about his first margin win last summer, over beers at that sticky-corner bar by the river. He was up 40% on a single cryptocurrency play, all on margin. Paid off half his student loan in one transfer. Showed her the clearinghouse alert on his phone, finger smeared on the glass. Said he used to sweat every tick like she did, until he realized “controlled burn” leverage spread out the fear. “Like accelerating through a skid,” he said. “Scared you’ll wreck, but if you don’t, you keep the line.” He genuinely believed it — still believes it, Felix checked last week. Dmitri checks his margin balance twice a day, waves a hand at anyone who flinches when he says “carry costs are negligible if you rotate fast.”

Noor didn’t rotate. She held. Then panicked when the stock dropped 18% on the first negative tweet from a grad student in Belgium. Margin call by 9:02 a.m. She transferred $3,000 — half her emergency savings — to avoid liquidation. Didn’t eat out for five weeks.

Felix mentioned it once, careful, like mentioning a rash. “You okay?” Noor said she was fine, but her new account rules are taped inside her laptop lid: no leverage until six months of flat buys, no single position over 3% portfolio, nothing with fewer than three quarterly filings. She’s now averaging eight trades a month, all cash, all index-heavy with small growth sidebets. Says she sleeps.

Dmitri still talks about “smart debt.” He doesn’t mention Noor when he does. But the next time he explained the strategy at dinner, mid-sentence, he paused, looked at his plate, and said, “Anyway. Maybe not for everyone.”

What to do instead? Don’t touch margin until you’ve lived through a down quarter without panic-selling. Until you can watch a 15% drop in a stock you like and not redraw your whole plan. Keep a cash-only account side-by-side, fund it monthly, trade only from it until the margin itch fades. If you must use leverage, use a paper version first — track fake margin buys for six months, including borrow rates and minimums. See if your math still works when the market opens down.

Dmitri still checks his alerts at 5:45 a.m. Noor starts her day at 7:15, after yoga. Says she reads the news like a novel now — just to see what happens, not because she has to act.

Felix told me yesterday: “She’s learning slower. But she’s not losing.”

