**FAQ: How do I know if financial advice I got is actually safe for my retirement stage?**

One of our regulars, Elena, came in last fall worried about her portfolio after a friend had suggested a shift she wasn’t sure about. She’d been in stable, income-focused instruments for years—bonds, dividend utilities, a few conservative funds. Her drawdown plan was modest, aligned with her timeline. She wasn’t seeking growth; she needed consistency.

The friend, Yuki, works in tech and has done well with concentrated plays—things like leveraged ETFs and early-stage private placements. What works for Yuki’s income level and risk tolerance isn’t typical for retirees, but it’s real to her. She’d mentioned in passing, over coffee, how much her crypto position had returned in two years. Elena asked if such things were viable for someone like her. Yuki said she thought so, especially if you held cash separately. She wasn’t selling a product, didn’t take a fee. Just spoke from her experience.

Elena moved 38% of her liquid assets into two vehicles: a cryptocurrency platform Yuki used and a small biotech stock Yuki had bought at IPO. Yuki believed the company’s trial data would trigger a buyout. Elena trusted the idea because Yuki seemed disciplined, always level-headed, and because the examples sounded logical in that moment—the “this could double” framing made sense when markets were rising.

It didn’t pan out. The biotech stock dropped 62% after trial results were delayed. The crypto platform froze withdrawals during a broader market dip. Elena couldn’t access the funds for five weeks. She started worrying about her next property tax payment.

She called Ingrid, another group member who’s been managing her own funds for years. Ingrid didn’t judge. First question: “Did you need that money on a timeline?” Elena said yes—within 18 months, she’d need some for a roof replacement. That changed the conversation. Ingrid helped her see it wasn’t about the returns, but the sequence risk and liquidity mismatch.

We helped her restructure—rebalanced into tiered CD ladders and a short-duration bond ETF, scaled back exposure to non-liquid holdings. Some of the crypto funds eventually came back, but not all. The biotech hasn’t recovered.

Yuki found out when Elena mentioned it in a group check-in. She was quiet for a long moment. Later, she brought in a typed note—handwritten first, she said, but she wanted it clear—and apologized. Not defensively. Just: “I thought I was helping. I didn’t see it from your side. I’m sorry.” She still uses those vehicles, but added, “I won’t talk about them with anyone in drawdown again.”

Elena’s stable now. Still cautious. Says she’ll listen, but cross-check more. “One person’s success,” she told us last month, “is just one person’s success.”

If something feels off—even if it comes from someone you trust—bring it in. We’ll look at it with you.

