Sanjay: And he told you to do it too.  

Devon: Said, “I made fifteen grand in three days. You’re sitting on safety like it’s a life raft in a swimming pool.”  

Sanjay: He wasn’t wrong about the rally. We all saw it.  

Devon: No. He wasn’t. And Owen’s not some scammer. He’s the guy who brought you soup when you had mono. He maxed out his own retirement years ago. This worked for him. Twice.  

Sanjay: So he thought it was a rule, not a fluke.  

Devon: Exactly. Thought the market had changed. That patience was for people who didn’t *get it*.  

Sanjay: And you?  

Devon: I hesitated. But he kept saying, “You only live once—unless you die broke.” Sounded smart at midnight.  

Sanjay: You cashed out.  

Devon: Fifty grand. Two weeks later, that biotech stock imploded. Lost thirty percent. Owen called again. Quiet. Said, “I’m sorry. I didn’t think it’d hit you like this.”  

Sanjay: What’d you say?  

Devon: Told him I was reevaluating.  

Sanjay: You still are?  

Devon: Still got the paperwork open. One tab says “withdrawal confirmation.” The other’s a retirement projection from twenty years ago. Age seventy. A little house near water.
